Polyurethane coating is a high-performance protective and waterproofing material made from synthetic polymers that cure to form a tough, elastic, and durable surface layer on building elements. It is widely used in construction for waterproofing roofs, balconies, terraces, parking decks, wet areas, and industrial floors because of its excellent flexibility, abrasion resistance, and strong adhesion to substrates such as concrete, metal, wood, and screed. Once applied, polyurethane coating forms a seamless and joint-free membrane that effectively prevents water penetration while accommodating thermal movement, structural vibration, and minor cracking without failure. It also offers good resistance to chemicals, oils, ultraviolet radiation (in UV-stable formulations), and weathering, making it suitable for both interior and exterior applications. Polyurethane coatings can be applied by roller, brush, or spray and are available in one-component or two-component systems, allowing flexibility in construction methods. Proper surface preparation and controlled application thickness are essential to achieve optimal performance and long service life. Although polyurethane coatings are more expensive than some traditional waterproofing systems, their durability, elasticity, and reliability make them a preferred solution for demanding environments where long-term protection and performance are critical.